{
  "What is the formula for density?": "",
  "Density = mass × volume": "",
  "Density = volume / mass": "",
  "Density = mass + volume": "",
  "Density = mass / volume": "",
  "Density is calculated as d = m/v (mass divided by volume). Common units include g/mL, g/cm³, and kg/m³. You can rearrange to find mass (m = d·v) or volume (v = m/d).": "",
  "If an object has a mass of 50 g and a volume of 25 mL, what is its density?": "",
  "25 g/mL": "",
  "2 g/mL": "",
  "75 g/mL": "",
  "0.5 g/mL": "",
  "Density = mass / volume = 50 g / 25 mL = 2 g/mL. The other choices result from multiplying, dividing reversed, or adding the values.": "",
  "An object with a density less than 1 g/mL will _____ in water.": "",
  "Sink": "",
  "Remain suspended in the middle": "",
  "Dissolve": "",
  "Float": "",
  "Water has a density of approximately 1 g/mL. Objects less dense than the surrounding fluid float; denser objects sink. If an object's density equals the fluid's, it remains neutrally buoyant.": "",
  "What is the density of water at standard conditions?": "",
  "100 g/mL": "",
  "0.1 g/mL": "",
  "10 g/mL": "",
  "1.00 g/mL": "",
  "Pure water at 4°C has a density of 1.00 g/mL (or equivalently, 1.00 g/cm³ or 1,000 kg/m³). This is a standard reference point for comparing other materials.": "",
  "How is the volume of an irregularly shaped solid typically measured?": "",
  "Water displacement — submerging it and measuring the volume change": "",
  "Heating it until it melts and measuring the liquid volume": "",
  "Using a ruler to measure length × width × height": "",
  "Weighing it on a balance": "",
  "For irregular shapes, water displacement is the standard method: fill a graduated cylinder with water, note the level, submerge the object, and read the new level. The difference equals the object's volume.": "",
  "If density remains constant and the mass of a sample doubles, what happens to volume?": "",
  "Volume halves": "",
  "Volume doubles": "",
  "Volume triples": "",
  "Volume stays the same": "",
  "Since d = m/v, if density is constant and mass doubles, volume must also double to keep the ratio the same: v = m/d, so doubling m doubles v.": "",
  "Which material has the highest density?": "",
  "Cork": "",
  "Lead": "",
  "Wood": "",
  "Air": "",
  "Lead has a density of about 11.3 g/cm³, far greater than wood (~0.5 g/cm³), cork (~0.12 g/cm³), or air (~0.001 g/cm³). Metals with heavy, tightly packed atoms typically have the highest densities.": "",
  "What are the common units for density?": "",
  "mL/g or cm³/g": "",
  "m/s or km/h": "",
  "kg or g": "",
  "g/mL or g/cm³": "",
  "Density is mass divided by volume, so its units combine a mass unit over a volume unit: g/mL, g/cm³, or kg/m³. Note that 1 g/mL = 1 g/cm³ because 1 mL = 1 cm³.": "",
  "Is density an intensive or extensive property?": "",
  "Neither — density is not a physical property": "",
  "Intensive — it stays the same regardless of sample size": "",
  "Both — it depends on the substance": "",
  "Extensive — it increases with more matter": "",
  "Density is intensive because when you increase the amount of matter, both mass and volume increase equally, keeping the ratio (d = m/v) constant. A gram of gold has the same density as a kilogram of gold.": "",
  "An object sinks in water but floats in mercury (density = 13.6 g/mL). The object's density must be:": "",
  "Less than 1 g/mL": "",
  "Between 1 g/mL and 13.6 g/mL": "",
  "Greater than 13.6 g/mL": "",
  "Exactly 1 g/mL": "",
  "The object sinks in water (density > 1 g/mL) but floats in mercury (density < 13.6 g/mL). Therefore its density falls between 1 and 13.6 g/mL. For example, iron (7.87 g/cm³) would behave this way.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'density'?": "",
  "The total volume of a substance": "",
  "The mass of a substance per unit volume, expressed as d = m/v": "",
  "The number of particles in a given sample": "",
  "The weight of a substance in air": "",
  "Density is defined as mass per unit volume. It describes how tightly matter is packed in a given space. Higher density means more mass concentrated in the same volume.": "",
  "What does 'buoyancy' mean?": "",
  "The speed at which an object sinks in a liquid": "",
  "The total mass of water displaced by an object": "",
  "The upward force exerted on an object by the fluid it is immersed in, determined by displaced fluid volume": "",
  "The downward force of gravity on an object in water": "",
  "Buoyancy is the upward force on an object submerged in a fluid. Archimedes' principle states this force equals the weight of the fluid displaced. If buoyant force exceeds gravity, the object floats.": "",
  "What does 'water displacement' mean in the context of measuring density?": "",
  "A method of measuring an object's volume by submerging it in water and recording the rise in water level": "",
  "Measuring how quickly water flows around an object": "",
  "Weighing an object underwater to find its mass": "",
  "Removing water from a container to make room for a solid": "",
  "Water displacement measures the volume of an irregular object. When submerged, the object pushes aside (displaces) a volume of water equal to its own volume. The change in water level in a graduated cylinder gives the volume.": "",
  "What does 'specific gravity' mean?": "",
  "The density of a substance measured in space (zero gravity)": "",
  "The mass of a substance at a specific temperature": "",
  "The ratio of a substance's density to the density of water — it is dimensionless (no units)": "",
  "The gravitational pull on a specific substance": "",
  "Specific gravity = density of substance / density of water. Since it is a ratio of the same units, it is dimensionless. A specific gravity greater than 1 means the substance sinks in water; less than 1 means it floats.": "",
  "What does 'graduated cylinder' refer to?": "",
  "A device that heats liquids to their boiling point": "",
  "A tube used to measure the density of gases": "",
  "A cylinder used to measure mass of solids": "",
  "A tall, narrow container with volume markings used to precisely measure liquid volume": "",
  "A graduated cylinder has volume markings (graduations) along its side and is used to measure liquid volumes precisely. Read the volume at the bottom of the meniscus (the curved surface of the liquid).": "",
  "What does 'meniscus' mean?": "",
  "The curved surface of a liquid in a container, caused by the interaction between the liquid and the container walls": "",
  "The flat surface of a liquid at rest when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "The steam rising from a heated liquid when evaluated systematically": "",
  "The bubbles formed when a liquid boils as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The meniscus is the curve at the top of a liquid column. Water forms a concave (dip down) meniscus in glass because water adheres to glass. Always read the volume at the bottom of a concave meniscus.": "",
  "What is 'mass' in chemistry?": "",
  "The space an object occupies, measured in liters": "",
  "The amount of matter in an object, measured in grams or kilograms": "",
  "The density of an object times its temperature": "",
  "The force of gravity acting on an object": "",
  "Mass is the quantity of matter in an object. It is constant regardless of location (unlike weight, which depends on gravity). Mass is measured using a balance and reported in grams (g) or kilograms (kg).": "",
  "What does 'volume' mean in the context of density?": "",
  "The weight of a substance at sea level": "",
  "The amount of three-dimensional space an object or substance occupies": "",
  "The temperature at which a substance changes state": "",
  "The loudness of a sound produced by a substance": "",
  "Volume is the space occupied by matter. It is measured in mL, L, or cm³. For regular shapes, volume = length × width × height. For irregular shapes, water displacement is used.": "",
  "What does 'Archimedes' Principle' state?": "",
  "All objects sink in water unless they contain air": "",
  "Mass and volume are always proportional to temperature": "",
  "Density determines the color of a substance": "",
  "An object submerged in a fluid experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced": "",
  "Archimedes' Principle: the buoyant force on a submerged object equals the weight of the displaced fluid. If this buoyant force exceeds the object's weight, the object floats. This principle allows us to use water displacement to measure volume.": "",
  "What does it mean for a substance to be 'neutrally buoyant'?": "",
  "The substance dissolves completely in the fluid": "",
  "The substance has zero mass in the fluid": "",
  "The substance's density equals the fluid's density, so it neither floats nor sinks": "",
  "The substance bounces between the surface and the bottom": "",
  "Neutral buoyancy occurs when an object's density exactly matches the surrounding fluid's density. The buoyant force equals gravity, so the object remains suspended at whatever depth it is placed. Submarines and scuba divers use this principle.": "",
  "A student measures the mass of a rock as 150 g. She places it in a graduated cylinder that contains 50 mL of water, and the water level rises to 80 mL. What is the density of the rock?": "",
  "3.0 g/mL — divide mass by final water level (150/50)": "",
  "2.0 g/mL — subtract water volume from mass (150 − 50 = 100, 150/100)": "",
  "5.0 g/mL — the rock's volume is 30 mL (80 − 50), and 150/30 = 5.0": "",
  "1.875 g/mL — divide mass by total volume (150/80)": "",
  "The rock's volume equals the water displaced: 80 mL − 50 mL = 30 mL. Density = mass/volume = 150 g / 30 mL = 5.0 g/mL. Common errors include dividing by the final reading or the initial reading instead of the difference.": "",
  "A cruise ship made of steel (density = 7.8 g/cm³) floats on water. If steel is much denser than water, why doesn't the ship sink?": "",
  "The ship's hull encloses a large volume of air, making the overall average density less than water": "",
  "Salt water is denser than steel, so all ships float in the ocean": "",
  "The ship's steel becomes less dense when shaped into a hull": "",
  "The engines push the ship upward to keep it from sinking": "",
  "Although steel is denser than water, the ship's hull is shaped to enclose vast volumes of air. The total mass of the ship (steel + air + cargo) divided by the total volume is less than 1 g/mL, so the ship's overall density allows it to float.": "",
  "A chef makes a layered drink by pouring honey, water, and oil into a glass. The honey settles at the bottom, water in the middle, and oil on top. What does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Liquids layer by density — honey is densest (bottom), water is in the middle, oil is least dense (top)": "",
  "The liquids are arranged by the order they were poured": "",
  "Lighter colors always float on top of darker ones": "",
  "Viscosity determines which liquid is on top": "",
  "When immiscible liquids are combined, they separate into layers based on density. Honey (~1.4 g/mL) is the densest and sinks. Water (1.0 g/mL) is less dense than honey but denser than oil (~0.9 g/mL), so it sits in the middle.": "",
  "A scientist has two metal cubes of the same size. Cube A has a mass of 27 g and Cube B has a mass of 216 g. She needs to determine which is aluminum (d = 2.7 g/cm³) and which is silver (d = 10.5 g/cm³). If each cube's volume is 10 cm³, which cube is which?": "",
  "Cube A is silver and Cube B is aluminum": "",
  "Cube A is aluminum (27/10 = 2.7 g/cm³) and Cube B is neither standard value — need to recheck mass": "",
  "Cube A is aluminum (27/10 = 2.7 g/cm³) and Cube B has a density of 21.6 g/cm³ — denser than silver, possibly gold or tungsten": "",
  "Both are aluminum because they are the same size": "",
  "Cube A: d = 27 g / 10 cm³ = 2.7 g/cm³, matching aluminum. Cube B: d = 216 g / 10 cm³ = 21.6 g/cm³, which does not match silver (10.5) — it is closer to platinum (21.4) or gold (19.3). Density calculations can reveal unexpected identities.": "",
  "Ice floats in liquid water, which is unusual for a solid-liquid pair of the same substance. How does this relate to density?": "",
  "Ice is denser than water but contains trapped air bubbles that make it float": "",
  "Ice is less dense (0.917 g/cm³) than liquid water (1.00 g/cm³) because its crystal structure has open spaces": "",
  "Water pushes ice upward due to surface tension, not density": "",
  "Ice and water have the same density, so ice just barely floats": "",
  "Water is one of the few substances whose solid form is less dense than its liquid. When water freezes, hydrogen bonds create an open hexagonal crystal structure with more space between molecules, reducing density to 0.917 g/cm³. This is why ice floats.": "",
  "A gold dealer receives a bar claimed to be pure gold (d = 19.3 g/cm³). She measures the mass as 500 g and the volume as 38 cm³. Is the bar likely pure gold?": "",
  "Cannot determine — mass and volume alone cannot identify a substance": "",
  "No — the calculated density is 13.2 g/cm³, much lower than gold; the bar is likely a cheaper metal or alloy": "",
  "Yes — 500 g is a reasonable mass for a gold bar": "",
  "Yes — 38 cm³ is a reasonable volume for gold": "",
  "Density = 500 g / 38 cm³ = 13.2 g/cm³. Pure gold has a density of 19.3 g/cm³, so this bar is significantly less dense. It could be lead (11.3) plated with gold, or a gold-copper alloy. Density is a reliable way to detect counterfeits.": "",
  "A hot air balloon rises because the air inside the balloon is heated. How does heating the air change its density?": "",
  "Heating removes air molecules from inside the balloon": "",
  "Heating makes air particles move faster and spread apart, decreasing the density below that of the surrounding cooler air": "",
  "The flame adds lighter gases that replace the original air": "",
  "Heating increases the air's density, which pushes the balloon upward": "",
  "Heating a gas increases particle speed and spacing, causing expansion. In an open balloon, some air escapes as it expands, reducing the mass inside while volume stays large. This lowers the overall density below the surrounding cool air, creating buoyancy.": "",
  "Dead Sea water has a density of about 1.24 g/mL. A swimmer who normally sinks in a freshwater pool finds they float easily in the Dead Sea. Why?": "",
  "The high salt content makes the swimmer lighter": "",
  "The Dead Sea has stronger waves that push swimmers up": "",
  "The warm temperature of the Dead Sea increases the swimmer's buoyancy": "",
  "The human body's density (~1.06 g/mL) is less than the Dead Sea water, so the buoyant force exceeds gravity": "",
  "The average human body has a density of about 1.06 g/mL. In freshwater (1.00 g/mL), this means we barely sink. In the Dead Sea (1.24 g/mL), the water is denser than the body, so the buoyant force is greater than the person's weight, and they float easily.": "",
  "A lab technician needs to separate a mixture of plastic beads: Bead A (d = 0.85 g/cm³), Bead B (d = 1.05 g/cm³), and Bead C (d = 1.35 g/cm³). She places them all in water. What happens?": "",
  "Bead A floats (less dense than water); Beads B and C sink (denser than water)": "",
  "Bead C floats and Bead A sinks": "",
  "All three sink because they are solid": "",
  "All three float because they are plastic": "",
  "Objects float if their density is less than the fluid they're in. Water's density is 1.00 g/cm³. Bead A (0.85) floats. Beads B (1.05) and C (1.35) are denser than water and sink. To further separate B and C, a denser liquid (e.g., salt water at 1.2 g/mL) could be used.": "",
  "An engineer designs a submarine that must operate at two depths: 100 m and 500 m. At 500 m, the water pressure compresses the sub's hull slightly, reducing its volume. If the sub's mass stays the same, what happens to its density, and how does this affect buoyancy?": "",
  "Density increases (same mass, less volume), reducing buoyancy — the sub tends to sink further unless it compensates": "",
  "Density decreases because water pressure pushes the sub upward": "",
  "Density stays the same because the sub is a solid object": "",
  "The sub floats more easily at 500 m because deeper water is denser": "",
  "If the hull compresses and volume decreases while mass stays the same, d = m/v increases. A denser submarine displaces less water relative to its weight, reducing buoyancy. Real submarines compensate by pumping water in or out of ballast tanks to adjust overall density.": ""
}